&gt; system got flooded with severe service disruptions.

&gt; The MTA has issued a report:

&gt; http://www.mta.info/mta/pdf/storm_report_2007.pdf

&gt; I am curious as to what people think of it.

&gt; [public replies, please]
">

It's been a few days and no one has taken the time to reply.  It is a
heavy read to find out that there are some things that no matter what
you do, service will be disrupted.  How much is the city willing to
spend to assure service during a 'Noah Flood&quot;?  Where do you draw the
line at how much water can be tolerated and how much is too much?

Without reading or (re-reading) in detail some points I remember:

There aren't enough buses and drivers available to cover the number of
subway passengers, even in a one or two line disruption, much less a
system wide outage (duh!).

Not to mention what about those passengers who only use the bus lines
when they lose their ride because the buses are diverted?

=======
The streets were flooded because the storm sewers couldn't handle the
water.  Water and stuff flows to the lowest point, the subway (duh!).

=======
The TA could do a better job of cleaning drains.  Where does the garbage
that clogs them come from?

=======
While the street furniture might look nice, they will take up space on
the sidewalks, so pedestrians won't be able to walk.

Hey, how about this:  put the sidewalk vendor stands over the subway
vents with duct work though the stand to make the opening seven feet
above street grade.  That will kill two birds with one stone and not
clog up the sidewalks any more than now.

========
Weather forecasting could be better.  I don't think any of the services
thought the storm would hit the city.  Most (all?) said it would pass
well to the north.  Wasn't there also a hurricane in the Gulf of Mexico
that 'popped up' suddenly this year?

========
The brunt of the storm hit after most passengers were on the way or
already on the system.  Even if cell phone text messages could work,
it's like tuning into a traffic report and hearing that there's a
traffic jam on the road you're stuck in.

========
MTA Bus and/or LI Bus never thought of rain as a major problem.

========
Within an hour or two of the end of the storm, most lines were back to
normal, except for balancing equipment.

========
They even mentioned global warming as a problem.

========
Bottom line, it was typical for this kind of report mandated by the
politicians, who probably won't want to spend the money that could
improve some of the things needed to help in future storms.

