I've used commercial forcasting services.

They are 'wrong' about as often as the NWS.

they tend to be wrong at _different_times_, so if they agree, there's a better
than usual chance of things hppening that way.

the commercial services will also forcast for your -specific- location.
as in how much rain you can expect overnight in _each_ field of your farm.

*EVERYBODY* uses the same basic weather model data.  There are only something
like five, I think it is, short-to-medium term weather models.a And only -two-
that attempt to model more  than 30 days out. *ONE* 5-day  forwared  analysis
run take about 14 hours  on the most powerful computer system of it's kind.

With _known_ uncertanties in the model output.  Local forcasts  are 'teweaked'
by what people see in 'local' conditions, and what that portends for the near
future.

I used to be incredibly accurate at predicting down-town chicago weather.
I could call the  start of precipitation up to 24 hours in advance, with
better than 15 minute precision.  No skill involved. I routinely got reports
from a location that was exactly 24 hours 'upweather' from the loop, under
normal conditions.  if it rained there at 2:40 on Tuesday, rain would hit the
Chicago loop at 2:40 on Wednensday.

I could only predict for Chicago.  but was much better than NWS or either of
two commercial services our company used.  Unfortunately, predicting for
Chicago was of liltle value to the company.  Not much farmland near
