I have no clue how long a third-rail segment is in NYTA, but assuming you
stop still in a live section; you could just suck from there.

Unlike the US household's 120v@20A outlet, you have many hundred KW
readily available, more than you can carry pumps and hose to use.

Hmm, I'm envisioning a 2 axle say 4 ft. long work platform. It's towed to
the site by the pumper consist. It holds an air-driven high volume but
low head pump, and maybe a small air-driven traction motor. A winch line,
discharge line and an air line will run from the consist.

The advantage of air is no one standing in water ever got cooked by an
air leak...and the EPA lets you spill air-laden water into the East
River.

The platform will proceed downhill from the consist into the flooded
area. It charges the discharge line, and the main pumper {say 50-500
ft away} then sucks from it and lifts to street/sewer level; or
where-ever. [This is what the fire dept does in some cases; one engine
feeds others.]

With this, you have ~2 feet of suction line. Discharge hose deploys and
stores far more easily than rigid suction line. The other plus is, the
only thing to get soggy will be the axle bearings, and submersible pumps.

