Penn Station and in the East River tunnels. &gt;&gt;

Usually...  :)

Same thing for Metro-North. I think most enginemen will
switch to electric mode while approaching the 97th street
portal to the Park Avenue Tunnel, but they will LEAVE THE
MAIN ENGINE RUNNING (but not developing traction power).

The reason is because on Metro-North, the push-pull trains
operate into G.C.T. with the cab car ahead and the diesel on
the rear of the train.

Because Grand Central is a busy place (particularly at rush
hours), it is not always possible for a train to get a
&quot;straight shot&quot; to the platforms without having to stop for
a signal for a movement ahead.

There is a slight upgrade from the throat of the terminal
towards the platforms. And also keep in mind that with
third-rail supplied power, there must be &quot;breaks in the
third rail&quot; at switches, crossovers, etc.

Now and then a train will stop with the engine on the rear
&quot;gapped&quot;: that is, the engine may have stopped in the middle
of a switch, and none of the third rail shoes are in contact
with the rail because of the gaps mentioned previously. It's
pretty hard to guess exactly where the engine is (in
relation to the gaps) when it's six, seven or eight cars
behind you.

If this happens, the only way to get out of the gap is to
switch back to the main diesel, change the locomotive back
to &quot;diesel mode&quot;, and power out of the gap - then switch
back to electric mode once you're back on the third rail.

Of course, getting the main engine started again if it has
been shut down takes a couple of minutes. And all the while,
the train isn't able to move, and thus is blocking up the
whole operation.

If the diesel engine is running - even at idle - things go
MUCH faster.

It's easier to leave the main engine running (but not under
load) until the train is actually entering the platform,
then shut it down and go totally on the electric.

Don't know how this reconciles with laws or operating rules,
but's that's the way it is....

- John
