They are not supposed to. They are supposed to operate on third rail
throught the Park Avenue Tunnel. The FL9s lost their third rail ability long
before they ceased operating into GCT; the Gennies are suppposed to have
their electric power in service. However, some use their diesel power in GCT
for various reasons, including gaps and the like.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; part of the way is electrified (Spuyten Duyvel &lt;-&gt; Croton.)
&gt; I don't know for a fact whether these locomotives go through
&gt; the East River tunnels, but, if not, where _are_ they serviced?
">

They use 3rd rail only in the short tunnel from the West Side line into Penn
Station and then on through the East River Tunnels. Diesel comes on for the
loop into SUnnyside and until the tunnel is encountered on their next
trip[ out.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; BTW, are the turbo-trains still in service?
">

No. NY had several rebuilt, but they are sitting at the Bear shops.

The Turbos all had third rail shoes -- some remember very well an Amtrak
Turbo starting up in GCT because it stalled on a long stretch of no third
rail through some puzzle switches -- and the hot blast from the stack just
**happenned** to be under a major telephone switching room thgat served
three midtown exchanges -- knocking out phone service for days and resulting
in lawsuits that took twenty years to settle.

Even the New Haven's lightweight and Talgos had third rail shoes. They had a
penchant for catching fire when making the switch on the Park Avenue
Viaduct. I think each of the three lightweights ruined one or more rush
hours  of NYC and NH commuters during the short time they were operational.

The LIRR uses dual modes as well though they are unreliable.

Cheers,
Jim Guthrie
