That law doesn't apply to anything now since it was repealed in 1930; it was
a pretty short-lived one, and more of a historical note than anything that
has a serious bearing on operations today.  Of course, once the requirement
was dropped, the lines had already paid the cost of electrifying, and
apparently they've considered it cheaper to keep maintaining that and use
dual-modes than go back to single-mode diesels.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I can tell you that &quot;rail transit&quot; and &quot;railroad corporation&quot; are
&gt; frequently regarded as two different animals.  Local regulations in our
&gt; city certainly apply to one but not the other.
">

If the regulations/laws/etc. were written specifically to cover one and not
the other, that's certainly possible.  Also, local attempts at regulation of
RRs are often preempted by federal laws and/or FRA regulations.  For
instance, a state (or city, if given that power by the state) could ban
whistles, but it would only apply to non-GRS RRs (e.g. non-FRA transit
operations) today.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Maintenance equipment (which is the only diesel powered equipment the New
&gt; York Subway would have) frequently doesn't qualify for a number of
&gt; regulations as well.
">

It's common for MOW and other specialty equipment to be exempted from most
regulations; the politicians usually only care about regulating the stuff
used in revenue service since that's all they see.

